<br>
I'll tackle this one first:  <br>
<br>
I don't like calling people &quot;retarded&quot; for not having much desire to restrain themselves unnecessarily.   In other words, you are *indeed* correct that group aggro management can overcome relatively weak warrior taunt.   Were this *not* true, the game would be almost totally unplayable for the warrior.   <br>
<br>
The question then becomes &quot;Does the warrior bring enough to the group to compensate for the extra stuff that we have to do?&quot;  I think most of us have learned that while this used to be true, it's becoming less and less so.  Enough people are still ignorant enough that we're not destitute *yet* but early identification and addressing of issues is *always* better than learning later and addressing after people leave in frustration.   <br>
<br>
For instance, Paladins used to suck.  They used to suck REALLY REALLY bad.  People used to not want to group with Paladins.  The *primary* reason for this was because of the experience penalty that a group would suffer due to the presence of a paladin.  Since this experience penalty no longer exists, I would argue that any attempt by any Paladin to claim &quot;a return to Kunark&quot; doesn't know what the hell he's talking about.   Now, Verant addressed Paladins' concerns (Lack of offense, Lack of Defense, Experience Penalty, Lack of a mana pool, sucky spells).  The problem was that they waited WAY too long.   People who had enjoyed playing Paladins pre-Kunark up and quit... re-rolled new toons, so on and so forth.   <br>
<br>
At the time, warriors were concerned that buffing up Paladins to almost warrior-like abilities would negatively affect warriors, but many saw the need anyhow, because playing a class that sucks.... sucks.   We also had inherent advantages that would STILL remain inherent advantages.   Advantages such as the highest AC/HP armor (by a respectable margin), kick or slam,  dual wield, and critical hits...not to mention /disc defensive (which wasn't that big of a deal until Velious), we had cool disciplines though.   We were reasonably satisfied that we'd retain some melee advantage, and we did for some time, too much some would argue.<br>
<br>
Then came Luclin, which really was the beginning of the decline of the warrior class.   Unique warrior specific advantages disappeared with Spell Casting Fury and Combat Fury AA's, warriors' little &quot;eye candy&quot; appeal was gone, it turned from cool to laughable.  Everyone went from &quot;oohh ahh... look a 500 point crippling blow&quot; to &quot;DID YOU SEE WHAT THAT PALADIN DID?&quot;   and &quot;Wow, the caster did THAT?&quot;   or &quot;Man, Ranger A is a god&quot;.  Warriors kept plinking away though.<br>
<br>
Mid Velious balancing began to rid the offensive advantage of dual wielding, and luclin itemization widened this, finally PoP mob design destroyed dual wield as an &quot;advantage&quot; and has turned it into a disadvantage.   Now the proposed 'solution' of 'just get yourself some EB weapons' while it sounds nice and dandy, it doesn't address the real problem, but worse, it's MORE dangerous if the EB weapons you choose (4 out of 6 EB/TB weapons are 1 handed, one is from Rallos Zek, the other is from an event that no one in their right mind would want to do).   <br>
<br>
Kick and Slam were an advantage because it allowed us the &quot;extra attack&quot; that others didn't get, and the opportunity to interrupt spellcasting (with slam from level 1, with kick from level 55).   In order for Knights to have this 'extra attack', they had to use a 1h weapon and a shield.  With AA's this is no longer true.  While this is not a major thing, it's yet another area where the warrior &quot;advantage&quot; has evaporated.<br>
<br>
We've gone over the warrior &quot;AC/HP on armor advantage&quot; ad naseum ad infinitum, but it bears repeating.   Until the Elemental planes, the best equipment wearable by warriors is also wearable by knights.   Again, this is a change from where it once was, and in my view, an unnecessary one at that.<br>
<br>
Itemization:  Luclin was crap for warrior itemization and PoP seems to be following suit.   We had the famous debates of &quot;If warrior and paladin are wielding the same weapon, then the warrior will out DPS Paladins&quot;.   The counter debate being &quot;When does THAT really happen seeing that there's a Pal/SK weapon on almost every boss encounter which exceeds what we have available to us?&quot;<br>
<br>
What it has turned into now is that the 'differences' while they USED to be extreme, are miniscule.   While warriors WERE overbalanced in relation to Paladins, the reverse is now true.   Precisely what warriors feared and were assured was never going to happen... happenned.   Now what we're left with is &quot;If warriors can do X, there's no reason to have a knight&quot;.  This is pure mularky, the fearmongering of 'returning to Kunark' is precisely that, nothing but fearmongering.  The reason that we will NEVER &quot;return to Kunark&quot; is because there is no experience penalty.<br>
<br>
Now, the advantages of Solid Aggro lock without corresponding grave consequences are visible to anyone willing to open their eyes and see.<br>
<br>
I've discussed this issue with DPS types and they UNIVERSALLY agree that there is a DPS cap based on aggro which is smaller than the DPS cap based on mana, by a factor of about 40DPS.   3 DPS types in a group who can raise their DPS by about 40 each exceeds the damage brought ENTIRELY by the warrior, not just the damage difference based on skill levels (which is closer to 20ish *if* using identical weapons, which is still a rarity).  If you disagree, I'll be happy to start a thread on Graffe's to verify this.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
for 4 the ending is hyperbole, &quot;Warrior aggro control makes that extremely risky.&quot; bullshit, I've never had a slower die on me because i couldn't taunt off of an initial slow (again no exageration). If you have because you couldn't get agro either you suck or your healer sucks, or the game really hates you. The slower could also have made a mistake as well, that being cani low, slow, get hit once, then low life agro kicks in, cleric doesn't heal in time and slower doesn't heal himself for whatever reason, etc. The rest of four falls apart with three. One root spell goes a long way.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Again, I don't think anyone's denying that there are acts that groups can perform which increase the likelihood of a warrior getting and maintaining aggro.   What we're all basically saying is that there's a serious imbalance in aggro generation (not maintenance) in relation to the corresponding difference in tankability between warrior and knight.<br>
<br>
Finally, I'd like to address an issue which a couple of people have brought up.   That being 'No one ever said we can't do some mob because we don't have a paladin'.   I'd like to know which mobs those were.  Generally speaking the only risky mobs I've seen that are 1-group targets are BoT minibosses.   Some groups prefer to have warriors doing them.   The fact though is that on at least 3 of them, a warrior is NOT the best tank for the job.   Certainly on Laef Windfall, he's definitely a 'warrior tank mob', because his damage is melee based, can be mitigated with defensive or evasive, but funny thing is that the reason he's a painful mob is because Slow works funny on him.   It actually LOSES effectiveness at various points throughout the fight.   He's unpredictable and unpredictability in mob melee damage is best handles by a warrior.<br>
<br>
Gaukr on the other hand, delivers his damage and &quot;spikyness' through a proc which warriors are not at any particular advantage over anyone else to avoid.   /disc defensive doesn't help at all with procs, so there's no real *need* to have a warrior tank even in a single group.   On the other hand, his damage is so extreme for a single group that you lose it and someone WILL die.   This is actually more beneficial for a paladin than a warrior.<br>
<br>
Oreen can easily be tanked by a Paladin and again, aggro control makes him the best choice.<br>
<br>
Hreidar is a puss who can ALSO be easily tanked by a paladin.   <br>
<br>
Now, these are mobs on a 6 hour respawn, as are most mini-named in PoP on long respawns.   Because *one* mob is best tanked by a warrior, because of spiky melee damage who is on a 6 hour respawn doesn't make warriors any more necessary in experience groups.    As a matter of fact, it's more like 'Dude, come tank Laef for me&quot; then &quot;see ya later&quot;. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=arothtb>Aroth TB</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>knows that Warriors are superior</span><br>  Posts: 14<br> <font color=#FF0000>(2/15/03 5:34 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthetavern.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1800.topic&index=189>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.steelwarrior.org/forum/p_ale.gif" align=absmiddle>  .</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Great. Wonderful. I've spent six months working on black smithing so I can make Barbarian cultural for myself. I've spent countless hours in NToV getting no drop gear. I have worked my ass off getting 25 AAXP. All so some SK with 2200 HP LESS can make me look like a chump because he can dance circles around me aggro control wise.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> <br>
